  "text": "Because D (Fig. 1A ) is identical at both values of F r , F r ϭ 1.0 and F r ϭ 2.0, it can be used to determine the required adjustments of p a and p b . First, calculate D for F r ϭ 1.0 [The quantiles (Q) or the probit values of gaussian distributions were obtained using the NORMINV function of the Microsoft Excel 97 program. Its arguments are proportion, mean, and standard deviation of the distribution, respectively]: [CITATION_1] We accounted in fact for ratios of SD up to 1.5 in our previous report on partitioning [CITATION_2] , because according to Harris and Boyd (4, [CITATION_3] , one of the proportions outside the common reference limits was guaranteed to exceed 4.0% when R Ͼ1.5. This cutoff value, considered as a separate criterion for partitioning by Harris and Boyd (4, [CITATION_4] , was originally determined using computer simulations. However, it is also possible to calculate this value. Such calculations, detailed in Appendix 1, which is published in a data supplement accompanying this article at Clinical Chemistry Online (www.clinchem.org/ content/vol48/issue11/), suggest that instead of R ϭ 1.5, it suffices to choose R ϭ 1.36 as an upper limit for R. As explained in Appendix 1, this value applies to any F r Ն1.0, which means that partitioning is needed whenever R Ն1.36. Because a lower value for the upper limit of R leads to better quality of the approximate critical distances, we will use the more precise value of 1.36 for it throughout this report. The second thing that we notice is that, whereas the original p a was below the critical proportion for partitioning, pCritP (4.1% or 0.041), the new p a exceeds this criterion. In other words, if D ϭ 0.40 s, partitioning is recommended at F r ϭ 2.0 but not at F r ϭ 1.0. This means, of course, that the critical distance corresponding to the critical partitioning proportion must be shorter for F r ϭ 2.0 than for F r ϭ 1.0. This is the case, because if distribution b is \"heavier\" than distribution a, the lower common reference limit follows closer to distribution b, which makes p a grow faster and reach the critical proportion at a shorter distance. Therefore, if a reference interval study is being carried out without consideration of the prevalences, it will be easy to make false decisions on partitioning. It is obvious that the relationship between the critical Fig. 2 . Illustration of the four topographic combinations of the subgroup distributions that need to be covered when developing generally applicable critical distances.",
